moxie

Class MoxieMatchers

  • java.lang.Object
    • moxie.MoxieMatchers
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    Moxie

    public abstract class MoxieMatchers
extends Object
    Static class whose methods magically signal Moxie to flexibly match parameters of a mock expectation.

     

    What are these methods?

    On certain method calls where you specify values that Moxie should expect as part of observed behavior - for example, method parameters on mock object calls, or return values on calls to spy objects - you can use the methods on MoxieMatchers to set flexible criteria for each parameter.

    These are used to generate Hamcrest Matchers which will be matched against the actual value(s).

     

    How do they work?

    (The gory details of the magic behind this class follow - you may safely skip to the next section if this bores/confuses you.)

    Every time you call a method on MoxieMatchers, a Matcher is pushed onto a stack, along with (in many cases, especially for primitives) an expected parameter type. The method then returns the default value (null for methods returning an object, zero/false for methods returning a primitive value).

    When you call a method that can take matcher invocations as parameters and the matcher stack is non-empty, the arguments to that method are examined from right to left. For arguments that are equal to the default value, the Matcher on top of the stack is popped off and used (unless it expects a value of an incompatible type, in which case an error is raised). For non-default arguments, an IsEqual matcher is created which will match on a value equal to that argument.

    When you call a method that can take matcher invocations as parameters and the matcher stack is empty, an IsEqual matcher is created for each parameter.

    At the end of this process, the matcher stack is checked, and an error is raised if it is non-empty. (Note that this does not occur in methods like and(), or() and not() which may themselves be part of matcher expressions.)

     

    What do I need to remember?

    • Never save the result of a call to MoxieMatchers to a variable - always plug it straight in to where it needs to go.
    • If you're using a MoxieMatchers call anywhere in a method call, make sure all zero/false/null parameters to that call are replaced with eq(0), eq(false) or isNull() respectively.

      • reportMatcher

        public static <T> T reportMatcher(org.hamcrest.Matcher matcher,
                                  Class<T> expectedType)
        Deprecated. This method is equivalent to argThat(expectedType, matcher). Use that method instead; for simplicity, this method will likely go away in a future release.
        Registers a Hamcrest Matcher with Moxie's magical parameter-matching mechanism.

        See the discussion in the summary javadoc for the MoxieMatchers class for more details.

        Type Parameters:
        T - type of the expected parameter
        Parameters:
        matcher - a Hamcrest Matcher to be registered
        expectedType - optional - type of the expected parameter (particularly important if matching a primitive parameter)
        Returns:
        null if expectedType is an object, or the primitive's default value if expectedType is a primitive
